UUssaaggee
       Here are some hints about files in /etc/rc.d:

       The order in which files are executed is important.  Since
       they  are executed in ASCII sort-sequence order, using the
       first character of the filename as  a  sequence  indicator
       will  help  keep  the  proper order.  Thus, files starting
       with the following characters would be: very  early  early
       later  last  Files  in /etc/rc.d that begin with a dot (.)
       will not be executed.  This feature can be  used  to  hide
       files that are not to be executed for the time being with-
       out removing them.  The command can  be  used  only  by  a
       privileged user.

       Files  in  /etc/rc2.d must begin with an S or a K followed
       by a number and the rest of the filename.   Upon  entering
       run  level 2, files beginning with S are executed with the
       start option; files beginning with K,  are  executed  with
       the  stop  option.   Files beginning with other characters
       are ignored.

